41
00:04:19,934 --> 00:04:28,559
And now I would like to introduce Justin Antos, Senior Director of Bus Transformation at the MBTA, who will begin this presentation.

42
00:04:29,000 --> 00:04:29,360
Justin?

43
00:04:34,216 --> 00:04:34,796
Thanks, Reagan.

44
00:04:36,317 --> 00:04:36,817
Good evening.

45
00:04:37,758 --> 00:04:38,958
My name is Justin Antos.

46
00:04:38,998 --> 00:04:50,144
I'm the Senior Director of Bus Transformation here at the T. I am excited to be here tonight to kick off this second public meeting in this phase for our bus network redesign.

47
00:04:51,044 --> 00:04:53,146
This is the second meeting on the topic.

48
00:04:53,586 --> 00:04:58,928
For those of you who tried to join the first but were unable, we apologize for the technical limits.

49
00:04:59,809 --> 00:05:01,930
And we thank you for joining tonight where we are back

50
00:05:02,437 --> 00:05:06,559
with a much higher participant limit on this Zoom platform.

51
00:05:07,559 --> 00:05:10,920
And for those who weren't able to get in, we apologize for that.

52
00:05:11,621 --> 00:05:12,721
Why am I excited tonight?

53
00:05:13,702 --> 00:05:20,704
Well, I think as we all can agree, transit is essential to our region's economy, and I'm excited about it.

54
00:05:21,085 --> 00:05:29,288
Especially post-pandemic, MBTA buses showed that they serve our most transit dependent populations.

55
00:05:30,255 --> 00:05:35,638
Early in the pandemic, bus ridership was the most resilient of all MBTA modes.

56
00:05:37,379 --> 00:05:44,242
But our region has changed over the past few years and decades, and we need a bus service that changes with it.

57
00:05:45,043 --> 00:05:52,867
It's essential that the MBTA's bus network adopts to how, where, and when people are traveling now, because it is different than what it was in the past.

58
00:05:55,248 --> 00:05:58,870
Back in May, we released a draft bus network proposal

59
00:05:59,627 --> 00:06:05,310
And over the summer, we received over 20,000 public comments on it.

60
00:06:06,230 --> 00:06:08,251
We've reviewed all of those.

61
00:06:08,551 --> 00:06:09,872
We've read all of them.

62
00:06:10,773 --> 00:06:25,480
And we've had dozens of meetings with cities, residents, elected officials, conversations at bus stops, and learned over the past few months of what folks liked and what folks didn't like about the proposal.

63
00:06:27,268 --> 00:06:30,090
We said that we would make meaningful changes based on what we heard.

64
00:06:31,250 --> 00:06:35,893
And we are here tonight to tell you about not only what we heard, but what we changed in response.

65
00:06:37,294 --> 00:06:42,037
I will say the public comment period for this specific proposal ended last summer.

66
00:06:42,977 --> 00:06:49,881
And the goal tonight is for us to explain what we heard last summer and also how we responded to it and how we changed in response.

67
00:06:51,122 --> 00:06:54,344
That said, our goal is still the same to create a better network

68
00:06:54,848 --> 00:07:04,932
more equitable service for our riders and transform the entire system by creating bus routes that are frequent, reliable, and connect to more places and are easier to use.

69
00:07:06,853 --> 00:07:07,513
How do we do that?

70
00:07:07,573 --> 00:07:12,735
We still plan to increase service by 25% across the network.

71
00:07:13,876 --> 00:07:18,238
We also plan to provide hundreds of thousands of riders with high frequency service.

72
00:07:18,958 --> 00:07:20,599
You'll hear that term a lot tonight.

73
00:07:21,399 --> 00:07:23,900
High frequency service means a bus route

74
00:07:24,491 --> 00:07:31,754
with a bus stopping at a bus stop every 15 minutes or better, all day long, seven days a week.

75
00:07:34,275 --> 00:07:44,180
Now, to make these improvements, we had to consider trade-offs and we were unable to make every change that you requested of us.

76
00:07:45,100 --> 00:07:53,864
We cannot please everyone all the time, but we did ultimately make changes to two thirds of the routes in the proposal that you will hear about tonight.

77
00:07:57,110 --> 00:08:01,691
So last, I'll close by saying that this is our bus network.

78
00:08:02,311 --> 00:08:07,613
It's not my bus network, it's not your bus network, it's not the MBTA's bus network, it is our network together.

79
00:08:08,413 --> 00:08:13,014
We know there are things in this plan that you like, and there are things in this plan that you might not like.

80
00:08:13,895 --> 00:08:17,015
But this is our bus system, and we care deeply about it.

81
00:08:17,155 --> 00:08:22,977
Everyone here on the team, including myself, ride the bus and care deeply about it.

82
00:08:24,077 --> 00:08:26,518
So I just wanted to say thank you for being here tonight,

83
00:08:27,142 --> 00:08:29,042
to help us build a better bus network.

84
00:08:30,243 --> 00:08:33,863
Now back to Doug Johnson, project manager for the Bus Network Redesign.

85
00:08:37,224 --> 00:08:37,904
Thank you, Justin.

86
00:08:38,504 --> 00:08:39,004
Hi, everyone.

87
00:08:39,164 --> 00:08:40,404
Thank you for joining us tonight.

88
00:08:41,085 --> 00:08:45,785
As Justin mentioned, my name is Doug Johnson, and I'm the project manager for Bus Network Redesign.

89
00:08:46,546 --> 00:08:53,907
Tonight's meeting will begin with a brief presentation about Bus Network Redesign and the changes that have been made to the proposal that we published back in May.

90
00:08:54,846 --> 00:09:01,094
As you all know, back in May, we published a draft network map, and we solicited public feedback on it through September.

91
00:09:01,815 --> 00:09:11,927
We ultimately received over 20,000 comments on the draft proposal, and we have incorporated that feedback into a revised network map that we will present to you tonight.

92
00:09:12,744 --> 00:09:23,192
I'll give a general overview of the changes that were made, and then we'll move into breakout rooms where project team members will give presentations about the changes made to specific areas of the network.

93
00:09:24,052 --> 00:09:28,575
In those breakout rooms, you will have the opportunity to ask questions about the changes that were made.

94
00:09:29,496 --> 00:09:35,060
After about an hour, we'll return to the main Zoom room for a Q&A session.

95
00:09:35,901 --> 00:09:38,743
At the start of the Q&A, we will call on elected officials first.

96
00:09:39,730 --> 00:09:52,220
If you are not able to stay for the whole meeting, but would like to leave a comment about the revised bus network, you can either post a comment in the chat, and we will add it to our records, or you can submit a comment through our online comment form.

97
00:09:52,881 --> 00:09:56,824
A link to that form will be posted in the chat for everyone to see.

98
00:09:59,370 --> 00:10:10,917
I'm going to keep my presentation here as brief as I possibly can so that we can go into the breakout rooms and folks can have the maximum amount of time to answer questions.

99
00:10:11,577 --> 00:10:20,563
But I do want to start by noting that bus network redesign is part of a much larger effort at the MBTA known as the Better Bus Project.

100
00:10:21,163 --> 00:10:36,173
The Better Bus Project is an initiative that's been ongoing for several years and encompasses a number of different efforts to transform, modernize, and decarbonize the entire MBTA bus fleet.

101
00:10:36,814 --> 00:10:40,977
That includes modernizing the maintenance and storage facilities,

102
00:10:41,717 --> 00:11:01,731
implementing bus transit priority across the network, things like bus lanes and signals specific for buses, as well as upgrading bus stops, making all of them accessible, changing the way that we collect fare on buses, and redesigning the entire bus network.

103
00:11:02,391 --> 00:11:06,914
So the bus network redesign is one facet of this larger effort and helps

104
00:11:07,995 --> 00:11:11,783
inform them and make all of them a possibility.

105
00:11:11,803 --> 00:11:19,418
The bus network redesign specifically is an effort to redesign the entire bus network

106
00:11:20,157 --> 00:11:23,058
so that it will better serve the needs of the region.

107
00:11:23,758 --> 00:11:28,900
As folks know, the bus network really hasn't changed very much in many decades.

108
00:11:29,160 --> 00:11:35,502
It's really a vestige of the old streetcar network that existed about 100 years ago.

109
00:11:35,522 --> 00:11:37,303
It hasn't really changed

110
00:11:38,345 --> 00:11:44,367
too much in that period of time, but the needs of the region have changed a lot.

111
00:11:44,927 --> 00:11:59,652
Even before the pandemic, changes in land use, changes in the way people get around, working hours, things like that, really created a mismatch between the bus network and the region.

112
00:12:00,112 --> 00:12:07,154
We're seeking to address that by redesigning the network so that it better meets the needs of people today.

113
00:12:10,232 --> 00:12:13,154
We started this process by prioritizing equity.

114
00:12:13,615 --> 00:12:28,007
That's the needs of the people who depend on bus service, most, including low income populations, communities of color seniors, people with disabilities, people who live in households with few or no vehicles.

115
00:12:30,013 --> 00:12:34,737
Those are people who are more likely to be dependent on transit to get around.

116
00:12:35,298 --> 00:12:43,765
So those are the people that we want to prioritize in this process and make sure that we're really serving as well as we possibly can with the new bus network.

117
00:12:45,676 --> 00:13:00,359
We're providing more frequent service in some of the most populated places, providing more all day service, creating new connections to more places, especially outside of downtown Boston, creating a network that's simpler and easier to use.

118
00:13:00,739 --> 00:13:10,641
And as I mentioned, creating more transit priority and other infrastructure to generally improve the reliability and accessibility of the bus network.

119
00:13:13,712 --> 00:13:21,956
We've developed this revised network using a set of service design principles and the public feedback that we received over the summer.

120
00:13:23,076 --> 00:13:36,563
We are prioritizing frequency over one-seat rides, creating more rapid transit connections and more crosstown routes, focusing on all-day service, to some extent combining routes to create high-frequency corridors,

121
00:13:37,620 --> 00:13:50,235
minimizing root variations and minimizing deviations on high frequency routes in order to improve reliability and make the network more legible and accessible to people.

122
00:13:52,557 --> 00:13:57,923
Public feedback was a really key component of planning the revised bus network.

123
00:13:58,944 --> 00:14:09,436
And we have reviewed all of the feedback that we received between May and September, including the feedback that we've received since then as well, because we keep getting more, of course.

124
00:14:10,418 --> 00:14:17,806
So we continue to review all that feedback, and we've incorporated the feedback into this revised network.

125
00:14:18,697 --> 00:14:21,298
As Justin mentioned, there are always trade-offs.

126
00:14:21,378 --> 00:14:30,142
We were not able to make every change that was asked of us, but we have designed a new network that is responsive to that feedback.

127
00:14:32,223 --> 00:14:39,826
The new bus network, just like as we proposed in May, would still increase service by 25% across the network.

128
00:14:42,505 --> 00:14:51,335
It doubles the number of high frequency corridors, which is a bus every 15 minutes or better, seven days a week from 5am to 1am.

129
00:14:51,955 --> 00:15:01,526
And when we say 15 minutes or better on many of those routes during certain periods of time like morning or evening rush hour, it would actually be more frequent than that.

130
00:15:02,066 --> 00:15:07,627
There are routes today that during rush hour are every four minutes or every eight minutes or every 11 minutes.

131
00:15:08,207 --> 00:15:11,928
And the intent is not to make those routes less frequent.

132
00:15:12,188 --> 00:15:26,532
The intent is to have 30 corridors across the Boston area where all day, every day, you know, on those routes, a bus is going to come every 15 minutes or more frequent than that.

133
00:15:27,248 --> 00:15:33,395
with the goal being that the routes are frequent enough that you don't even have to check a schedule.

134
00:15:33,695 --> 00:15:39,922
You know that you can just go to your bus stop and that in less than 15 minutes, you'll be getting on a bus there.

135
00:15:43,083 --> 00:15:51,427
We ended up making changes to two thirds of the routes that we had in that May proposal due to the public feedback that we got.

136
00:15:52,047 --> 00:16:08,075
The changes range from really small changes to the way a bus is routed through a neighborhood to wholesale changes to routes, in some cases, putting routes back the way that they are functioning today or functioned pre-COVID.

137
00:16:08,896 --> 00:16:11,017
So the changes really run the gambit

138
00:16:11,851 --> 00:16:13,373
from one end of that scale to the other.

139
00:16:14,214 --> 00:16:16,057
There were five main reasons why we made changes.

140
00:16:16,717 --> 00:16:18,640
The first was to respond to public feedback.

141
00:16:19,461 --> 00:16:26,469
The second was to improve access to hospitals, senior centers, and other destinations like grocery stores and shopping centers.

142
00:16:27,424 --> 00:16:40,849
The third was to reduce walk distances, especially for seniors and other riders like people with disabilities or mobility impairments, and especially in places with really challenging topography.

143
00:16:41,449 --> 00:16:50,372
There are certain parts of the bus network that are really hilly, and that can pose a really big challenge for folks trying to access bus service.

144
00:16:50,953 --> 00:16:51,673
In some cases,

145
00:16:52,812 --> 00:17:01,656
route may only be a block or two away but if it's up or down a really steep hill for many of our riders that can make that service inaccessible.

146
00:17:02,837 --> 00:17:07,459
The fourth reason was to preserve some existing one-seat rides to many destinations.

147
00:17:07,699 --> 00:17:16,263
So that's a situation where right now you get on a bus at point A and it takes you directly to point B and you don't have to make any transfers.

148
00:17:17,305 --> 00:17:26,852
In this new network, for some trips, there will be situations where folks that have a one-seat ride today may have to make a transfer to another service.

149
00:17:27,493 --> 00:17:41,163
But based on the feedback that we got on that draft network that we put out in May, we looked at many of those situations and in some cases put some of those one-seat rides back to the way they function today based on the feedback that we heard.

150
00:17:42,338 --> 00:17:49,355
The fifth reason for changes was to balance resources and make sure that we stay within the hard limits that we have.

151
00:17:50,179 --> 00:17:53,860
there are a maximum number of buses that we can run at any given time.

152
00:17:54,180 --> 00:17:56,781
So that's a hard limit that we have to stay within.

153
00:17:57,601 --> 00:18:01,602
And then there's the budgeted service amount that we had to stay within as well.

154
00:18:01,922 --> 00:18:12,285
And that's still 25% above the amount of service that was provided when I say today, in this case, what I mean is the amount of service that was provided pre COVID.

155
00:18:15,340 --> 00:18:19,642
This slide shows a general summary of many of the changes that we made.

156
00:18:19,662 --> 00:18:23,343
Not every route is listed here, but I do want to highlight some.

157
00:18:24,364 --> 00:18:30,926
There are some routes that we restored to their existing routing, either in part or in whole.

158
00:18:32,747 --> 00:18:34,668
The 55 is an example of that.

159
00:18:34,928 --> 00:18:40,130
So that route is going to continue to do what it does today, as opposed to what we had proposed back in May.

160
00:18:41,883 --> 00:18:46,306
The 47, part of it is in the new network.

161
00:18:46,646 --> 00:18:48,627
That was a route that was not in the May proposal.

162
00:18:48,987 --> 00:18:50,048
Part of it's in the new network.

163
00:18:50,488 --> 00:18:54,291
It also does some other things in addition to part of what it does today.

164
00:18:54,311 --> 00:19:00,035
I also want to mention the 354 is a route that we put back.

165
00:19:02,937 --> 00:19:10,002
The T39 is a route that we put back basically to what it does today from JP to Copley and Back Bay.

166
00:19:11,207 --> 00:19:20,371
Then there were routes that we rerouted to better provide better connections to medical facilities, senior housing, and other destinations, as I mentioned.

167
00:19:21,772 --> 00:19:26,094
Routes like the 8, the 11, and the 12 were all changed.

168
00:19:26,334 --> 00:19:32,416
The 11 will now serve Tufts Medical Center from South Boston, as it does today.

169
00:19:32,436 --> 00:19:36,918
The 8 and the 12 were modified to better serve Boston Medical Center.

170
00:19:41,085 --> 00:19:44,686
And you can see many other routes here that we modified for similar reasons.

171
00:19:45,966 --> 00:19:51,267
There were some routes that we added to the new bus network that were not in that May proposal.

172
00:19:52,287 --> 00:19:58,228
Many of these were routes that we added in addition to some of the other changes that were made.

173
00:19:58,248 --> 00:20:08,450
The 113 is a brand new route from Chelsea to Somerville that is a one-seat ride from Chelsea to Assembly Row.

174
00:20:09,769 --> 00:20:13,831
And then there were some routes where we modified the frequency or span of service.

175
00:20:14,051 --> 00:20:21,896
So that's how often it runs or what times of day it runs, but where we didn't make changes to the route themselves.

176
00:20:22,476 --> 00:20:27,639
So the SL2, we had proposed it being peak period only on weekdays.

177
00:20:28,139 --> 00:20:32,222
The SL2 will continue to be seven days a week in this new network.

178
00:20:33,362 --> 00:20:41,725
then there were some routes that had been included in the May proposal but are not in the proposal now due to other changes that we made.

179
00:20:42,425 --> 00:20:50,928
So the 20 was a route that had been in the May proposal, we've removed it because we put the 201 and 202 back to the way they are today.

180
00:20:51,588 --> 00:20:57,670
So many of these changes are related to one another and when we go into breakout rooms the facilitators in those rooms

181
00:20:58,390 --> 00:21:07,677
will speak in more detail about these routes and they will show you maps that allow you to see what the change was from the May proposal to now.

182
00:21:11,240 --> 00:21:14,743
Information about the revised bus network is publicly available.

183
00:21:15,383 --> 00:21:23,830
The list of changes made to the main network is posted on the project website along with an interactive map and a static PDF map.

184
00:21:24,492 --> 00:21:31,740
There is also an online comment form where folks can submit comments to the project team about the revised network map.

185
00:21:32,862 --> 00:21:45,356
An equity analysis of the revised network is underway and will be completed by December, and there'll be a public meeting on the evening of December 8th to present the results of that equity analysis.

186
00:21:48,328 --> 00:21:56,053
We anticipate implementation of the new network to take about five years, beginning in 2023.

187
00:21:56,574 --> 00:22:09,363
And over that five year period, we intend to make changes to routes incrementally every year until by the fifth year of implementation, the whole network is in place.

188
00:22:11,450 --> 00:22:18,031
The MBTA and many transit agencies across the country are facing bus operator shortages at the moment.

189
00:22:18,351 --> 00:22:36,815
And as you all know, this is something that we are working to address as we go through the phases of implementation, with the intent being that we will increase our operator headcount over this period of time so that by year five, when the whole network is in place,

190
00:22:37,315 --> 00:22:43,078
who will have all the operators on board necessary to provide this increased level of service.

191
00:22:46,520 --> 00:22:54,724
You can continue to stay informed about this project and the process of implementation by going to the project website.

192
