602
01:16:15,597 --> 01:16:21,381
So it's trading the one Alewife terminus for a red and a green.

603
01:16:22,182 --> 01:16:30,509
And there may be folks who are traveling locally along Mass Ave, which would still be served by the T77 bus for folks who are looking to transfer.

604
01:16:36,957 --> 01:16:37,178
OK.

605
01:16:38,098 --> 01:16:42,240
The 94 bus, is that route going away?

606
01:16:42,700 --> 01:16:45,741
And specifically, is there a route going up and down Boston Avenue?

607
01:16:47,002 --> 01:16:47,222
Right.

608
01:16:47,422 --> 01:16:50,683
So in the new proposal, there is no 94.

609
01:16:51,123 --> 01:17:01,087
There would still be service up and down Boston Avenue on the 80, but it would be the only bus that is on Boston Avenue, unlike today where you have both the 80 and the 94.

610
01:17:03,402 --> 01:17:07,623
by kind of decreasing the number of routes that we have overall.

611
01:17:07,943 --> 01:17:18,707
That's one of the trade-offs that we were able to make so that we could make a lot more high frequency routes, so that we could make the T96 be every 15 minutes or better, so that we could make the T101

612
01:17:19,707 --> 01:17:21,628
be every 15 minutes or better seven days a week.

613
01:17:21,648 --> 01:17:24,930
So there may be fewer routes on the map.

614
01:17:25,150 --> 01:17:41,820
And yes, there's not a 94 in the proposed new network, but there's still more service hours because the routes that are there, we've generally tried to make more of those high frequency, high quality routes, but that takes resources.

615
01:17:42,261 --> 01:17:48,825
So the way that we were able to kind of afford some of those changes besides we're also adding resources, but that also took

616
01:17:50,266 --> 01:17:56,309
sometimes reducing the number of direct connections that you can get to from a certain location.

617
01:17:56,329 --> 01:18:03,293
All right, a couple of implementation questions.

618
01:18:04,174 --> 01:18:09,357
How do you plan to address bus bunching and are there still going to be changes from this version of the proposal?

619
01:18:12,715 --> 01:18:13,295
Great question.

620
01:18:13,475 --> 01:18:17,296
So bus bunching is something that we're still very interested in.

621
01:18:17,316 --> 01:18:24,258
I would say that's something that we can work on in parallel with thinking about where the routes go.

622
01:18:25,558 --> 01:18:35,240
So the bus network redesign is one piece of an overall program that we're calling the Better Bus Project that is looking at how we can transform bus service and make it better.

623
01:18:35,720 --> 01:18:42,242
As part of that, there are other things that we are doing, looking at things like how do we improve dispatching, or honestly,

624
01:18:43,362 --> 01:18:53,885
even with getting more operators, that can address some of the bunching issues we might have just from not having enough resources on the line to begin with.

625
01:18:54,566 --> 01:19:07,970
But we're also looking to partner with municipalities to look at opportunities for signal priority or other transit, either signal priority or other priority features like lanes,

626
01:19:08,530 --> 01:19:15,993
queue jumps, stop consolidation, many different tools that we have in the toolkit that can help improve bus service.

627
01:19:16,953 --> 01:19:25,737
And then, you know, it's not all about the infrastructure, we're separately working with our customer technology department to look at ways to

628
01:19:26,237 --> 01:19:48,658
you know, give our dispatchers better tools so that they can monitor service at the end of the line, make sure that things are, especially for those frequent services where it's, you know, just trying to maintain regular even spacing, you know, how can we make sure that we're dispatching appropriately, that things are leaving at least from the ends of the line reliably.

629
01:19:49,139 --> 01:19:51,040
Now that said, I know there can be

630
01:19:53,056 --> 01:19:58,677
delays that accumulate along the route, but making sure that terminal operations work well.

631
01:19:58,717 --> 01:20:19,181
So there's many different things that we would be looking to do as part of the larger Better Bus project to think about bus bunching, but that's kind of like a parallel track to what we're talking about here, which is the bus network redesign and where the routes go and how frequently the buses come, et cetera.

632
01:20:25,315 --> 01:20:27,296
